  "Steady, prolonged precipitation": "",
  "Only strong wind": "",
  "Lightning only": "",
  "Clear skies": "",
  "Nimbostratus clouds are thick, dark, low-to-mid level clouds that produce continuous, steady precipitation (rain or snow) over wide areas, often associated with warm fronts or large-scale low pressure systems.": "",
  "Clouds form when air rises and:": "",
  "Absorbs additional moisture from space": "",
  "Cools to its dew point, causing water vapor to condense on condensation nuclei": "",
  "Loses all pressure instantly": "",
  "Heats up and expands": "",
  "As air rises, it expands and cools adiabatically, and when it reaches the dew point temperature, the water vapor in the air condenses onto tiny particles called condensation nuclei to form the water droplets or ice crystals that make up clouds.": "",
  "Condensation nuclei are:": "",
  "Not needed for cloud formation": "",
  "Large water drops that form clouds": "",
  "Tiny particles such as dust, pollen, salt, or pollution that water vapor condenses onto": "",
  "Ice cubes suspended in the atmosphere": "",
  "Condensation nuclei (also called cloud condensation nuclei or CCN) are microscopic particles in the atmosphere that provide surfaces for water vapor molecules to condense onto, and without them, clouds would not form even in saturated air.": "",
  "The Bergeron process operates in clouds that contain:": "",
  "Both ice crystals and supercooled liquid water": "",
  "Only warm air": "",
  "Only ice crystals": "",
  "Only liquid water": "",
  "The Bergeron process occurs in mixed-phase clouds where ice crystals and supercooled water droplets coexist, and because ice crystals grow at the expense of the water droplets (due to lower vapor pressure over ice), they can grow large enough to fall as precipitation.": "",
  "Collision-coalescence is the primary precipitation process in:": "",
  "Warm tropical clouds where cloud tops do not reach freezing": "",
  "All clouds equally regardless of temperature": "",
  "Only high-altitude cirrus clouds": "",
  "Cold clouds near the poles": "",
  "In warm tropical clouds where temperatures remain above freezing throughout, precipitation forms through collision-coalescence, where larger droplets collide with and absorb smaller ones as they fall, growing until they are heavy enough to fall as rain.": "",
