  "Cumulus cloud": "",
  "Fog is a stratus-type cloud that forms at or very near the ground surface when air near the surface cools to its dew point or when moist air moves over a cool surface, reducing visibility to less than 1 km.": "",
  "Orographic precipitation occurs when air is forced upward by:": "",
  "Convective heating": "",
  "Cold fronts": "",
  "Low pressure systems only": "",
  "Mountains or elevated terrain": "",
  "Orographic precipitation occurs when moist air is forced to rise over mountains or elevated terrain, cooling as it ascends until condensation and precipitation occur on the windward side, while the leeward side remains dry in what is called a rain shadow.": "",
  "Hail forms in:": "",
  "Stratus clouds during winter": "",
  "Fog near the ground surface": "",
  "Cumulonimbus clouds with strong updrafts": "",
  "Cirrus clouds at high altitude": "",
  "Hail forms in powerful cumulonimbus clouds where strong updrafts repeatedly lift ice particles through the cloud, adding layers of ice with each cycle, until the hailstone becomes too heavy for the updraft to support and falls to the ground.": "",
  "What is the rain shadow effect?": "",
  "The dry conditions on the leeward side of a mountain where descending air warms and dries out after moisture was released on the windward side": "",
  "The area of reduced rainfall directly beneath a thunderstorm": "",
  "The shadow cast by tall rain clouds that blocks sunlight": "",
  "The cooling effect that rain has on the surrounding air": "",
  "The rain shadow effect creates dry conditions on the leeward (downwind) side of mountains because air that rises over the windward side loses its moisture as precipitation, and as it descends on the other side, it warms and becomes even drier.": "",
  "What is sleet?": "",
  "Rain that freezes inside a cloud": "",
  "Snow that partially melts and then refreezes on contact with the ground": "",
  "Rain that falls through a subfreezing layer near the surface and freezes into ice pellets before hitting the ground": "",
  "Frozen fog that forms on cold surfaces": "",
  "Sleet forms when rain or melted snow falls through a layer of air near the surface that is below freezing, causing the liquid drops to freeze into small ice pellets before they reach the ground, producing a bouncing effect on impact.": "",
  "What is freezing rain?": "",
  "Ice pellets that bounce when they hit the ground": "",
  "Rain that turns into snow as it falls": "",
  "Rain that remains liquid until it contacts a surface below 0 degrees Celsius and freezes on impact": "",
  "Hail that melts slightly before hitting the ground": "",
  "Freezing rain occurs when rain falls through a shallow subfreezing layer at the surface and remains in liquid form until it contacts cold surfaces (roads, trees, power lines), where it immediately freezes into a dangerous glaze of ice.": "",
