  "A city on the western (windward) side of a mountain range receives 2,000 mm of annual precipitation, while a city on the eastern (leeward) side at the same latitude receives only 250 mm. This dramatic difference is caused by:": "",
  "The eastern city having less vegetation to attract rainfall": "",
  "The rain shadow effect, where air loses moisture on the windward side and descends dry on the leeward side": "",
  "The eastern city being closer to the equator": "",
  "Different ocean currents affecting each side of the mountains": "",
  "The rain shadow effect explains this difference: moist air is forced upward on the windward side, cools, and drops heavy precipitation, then descends on the leeward side, warming and drying out, creating near-desert conditions.": "",
  "An ice storm warning is issued for a region where rain is expected to freeze on contact with surfaces. The atmospheric temperature profile that creates freezing rain includes:": "",
  "A warm layer aloft where snow melts into rain, then a shallow freezing layer at the surface where the rain remains liquid until it contacts subfreezing surfaces": "",
  "Below-freezing temperatures from the cloud to the ground": "",
  "A deep freezing layer that converts rain to sleet well above the ground": "",
  "Above-freezing temperatures throughout the entire atmosphere": "",
  "Freezing rain requires a specific temperature profile: snow falls from the cloud, melts into rain in a warm layer aloft, and then passes through a shallow subfreezing layer at the surface that is not deep enough to refreeze the drops, so they freeze only on contact with cold surfaces.": "",
  "A pilot flying over the tropics encounters heavy rain from clouds whose tops do not reach the freezing level. The precipitation process in these clouds is most likely:": "",
  "Orographic lifting caused by tropical mountains": "",
  "The Bergeron process, relying on ice crystals": "",
  "Cloud seeding by natural salt particles from the ocean": "",
  "Collision-coalescence, where larger droplets grow by merging with smaller ones as they fall": "",
  "In warm tropical clouds where temperatures remain above freezing throughout, the Bergeron ice-crystal process cannot operate, so precipitation forms entirely through collision-coalescence where larger drops fall faster and collide with smaller, slower drops.": "",
  "A farmer in the Great Plains sees large hailstones falling during a severe thunderstorm. The hailstones are the size of golf balls, indicating that the storm likely has:": "",
