  "Florida's summer thunderstorms typically form through convective processes as intense solar heating warms the moist surface air, combined with converging sea breezes from both coasts, forcing air upward to create towering cumulonimbus clouds.": "",
  "A traffic advisory warns of freezing rain along a highway, but just 50 km to the north, the same storm is producing sleet. The difference between these two precipitation types is due to:": "",
